    <div id="entry-323">
	<div class="entry-header">
		<h2 class="asset-name entry-title"><a href="http://www.encs.concordia.ca/news-and-events/entry.php?a=2011/03/27th-troitsky-competition-a-crushing-success.php">27th Troitsky Competition a Crushing Success</a></h2>
		<div class="entry-meta" title="2011-03-11T10:50:11-05:00">Friday Mar 11, 2011
                </div>
	</div>

	<div class="entry-content">
	
		<div class="entry-body">
			As part of the Engineering Week festivities, Concordia's Faculty of Engineering and Computer Science opened its doors on Friday, March 4, for the 27th annual Troitsky Bridge Building Competition. A grand total of 36 teams of undergraduate engineering students from universities ranging from Carleton to Calgary, McMaster to Vermont came to Concordia to participate in this creative competition that really puts engineering abilities to the test.<br /><br /><object height="300" width="400"> <param name="flashvars" value="offsite=true&amp;lang=en-us&amp;page_show_url=%2Fphotos%2Fencs-concordia%2Fsets%2F72157626114450839%2Fshow%2F&amp;page_show_back_url=%2Fphotos%2Fencs-concordia%2Fsets%2F72157626114450839%2F&amp;set_id=72157626114450839&amp;jump_to=" /> <param name="movie" value="http://www.flickr.com/apps/slideshow/show.swf?v=71649" /> <param name="allowFullScreen" value="true" /><embed type="application/x-shockwave-flash" src="http://www.flickr.com/apps/slideshow/show.swf?v=71649" allowfullscreen="true" flashvars="offsite=true&lang=en-us&page_show_url=%2Fphotos%2Fencs-concordia%2Fsets%2F72157626114450839%2Fshow%2F&page_show_back_url=%2Fphotos%2Fencs-concordia%2Fsets%2F72157626114450839%2F&set_id=72157626114450839&jump_to=" height="300" width="400"></object><br /><br />The idea behind Troitsky is simple: using only Popsicle sticks, white school glue and dental floss, teams are given just two hours to build a bridge that can withstand a heavy load--while&nbsp; taking efficiency, originality, and aesthetics into account. <br /><br />After the two hours are up, it's time for the judges to make their rounds. This year's team of volunteer officials were Ivan Antolin (Vice-President of Montage D'Acier International), Pierre-Albert Jean (President and CEO of Construction Albert Jean Ltd.), and our very own Lucia Tirca (Assistant Professor in the Department of Building, Civil and Environmental Engineering). The three toured the entries, judging the bridges based aesthetics &amp; originality of the idea, and booth layout &amp; presentation--and were amply impressed with what they saw!<br /><br />But the competition wouldn't be complete without the fourth and final judge: a hydraulic press nicknamed the Crusher. This special machine (generously donated to the Faculty by Mechtronix several years ago, after the first Crusher crushed itself in a Troitsky-related mishap!) tests the bridges for ultimate load carrying capacity and structural efficiency. This part of the event is inevitably the loudest and most raucous. The auditorium in the JMSB building was filled with cheers and chants--and the sounds of wooden bridges that finally succumbed to the pressure.<br /><br />Final results are still being tabulated (and will be posted on this website as soon as they are made available) but it's worth noting that the bridge built by last year's winners, McMaster University's League of Extraordinary Gentlemen, actually reached 2950 kilogram force... at which point the Crusher had to be turned off because some strange sounds were leading the lab technician to fear it would break. That bridge's ultimate capacity will just have to remain a mystery!<br /><br />To check out all the Troistyite fun, be sure to take a peek at the event photos on our <a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/encs-concordia/sets/72157626114450839/">Flickr page</a>.<br /><br />
		</div>
	
	</div>
</div>
<div class="clear">&nbsp;</div>



    

    <div id="entry-319">
	<div class="entry-header">
		<h2 class="asset-name entry-title"><a href="http://www.encs.concordia.ca/news-and-events/entry.php?a=2011/03/ciise-study-receives-international-attention.php">CIISE study receives international attention </a></h2>
		<div class="entry-meta" title="2011-03-09T11:31:21-05:00">Wednesday Mar  9, 2011
                </div>
	</div>

	<div class="entry-content">
	
		<div class="entry-body">
			<span style="font-family: 'Arial','sans-serif';">Researchers with the Concordia Institute for Information Systems Engineering have developed an effective new technique to determine the authorship of anonymous emails. The study has received international coverage, in <a href="http://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2011/03/08/Anonymous-e-mail-senders-can-be-identified/UPI-29051299645855/">UPI</a>, <a href="http://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2011-03/09/anonymous-email-identification">Wired</a> (UK), <a href="http://www.thestar.com/news/canada/article/950625--canadian-scientists-crack-code-for-tracing-anonymous-emails">Toronto Star</a>, <a href="http://www.ibtimes.com/articles/120339/20110308/cybercrime-anonymous-emails-data-mining-concordia-university.htm">International Business Times</a>, <a href="http://www.pcworld.com/businesscenter/article/221651/researchers_unmasking_anonymous_email_senders.html">PC World</a>, <a href="http://www.securecomputing.net.au/News/250654,researchers-mine-emails-for-criminal-characteristics.aspx">Secure Computing Magazine</a> (Australia), <a href="http://computerworld.co.nz/news.nsf/security/researchers-unmasking-anonymous-email-senders">Computer World</a> (New Zealand), <a href="http://www.thinq.co.uk/2011/3/8/anonymous-email-authors-can-be-traced/">Thinq</a> (UK), <a href="http://www.metronews.ca/toronto/local/article/796915--your-e-mail-writeprint-will-trap-you">Metro Canada</a>, <a href="http://news.techworld.com/sme/3264250/email-anonymity-breached-by-canadian-researchers/">TechWorld</a>, <a href="http://www.cio.com/article/675270/Researchers_Unmasking_Anonymous_E_Mail_Senders?source=rss_news">CIO Magazine</a>, <a href="http://www.rdmag.com/News/Feeds/2011/03/information-tech-identifying-anonymous-email-authors/">R&amp;D Magazine</a>, <a href="http://www.gizmag.com/identifying-authors-of-anonymous-emails/18091/">Giz Mag</a>, <a href="http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/tech/internet/researchers-develop-new-technique-that-can-quash-cyber-crimes/articleshow/7663376.cms">the Economic Times</a>, <a href="http://inventorspot.com/articles/slamming_scamming_spammers_how_identify_anonymous_email_authors">Inventors Spot</a> and <a href="http://www.theinquirer.net/inquirer/news/2032285/anonymous-emails-traced">The Inquirer</a>. </span><span style="font-family: &quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;">The study has also received coverage in the <a href="http://www.ahmedabadmirror.com/article/30/20110310201103100327002012c70a648/Tracking-anonymous-emails.html">Ahmedabad Mirror</a> (India), <a href="http://www.idg.se/2.1085/1.373090/sa-knacker-forskarna-anonyma-mejl">IDG News</a> (in Swedish), <a href="http://www.networld.pl/news/367969/Tworcy.anonimowych.e.maili.powinni.sie.miec.na.bacznosci.html">NetWorld</a> (in Polish), <a href="http://communities.canada.com/montrealgazette/blogs/universitycity/archive/2011/03/08/concordia-s-benjamin-fung-and-the-mystery-of-anonymous-email.aspx">University City blog</a>, <a href="http://www.ubergizmo.com/2011/03/identify-anonymous-email-senders/">UberGizmo</a>, <a href="http://www.pcpro.co.uk/news/security/365839/fingerprints-show-who-sent-anonymous-emails">PC Pro</a> (UK) and <a href="http://www.developpez.com/actu/29407/On-pourra-bientot-identifier-les-auteurs-de-mails-anonymes-via-leurs-empreintes-digitales-numeriques-d-apres-des-chercheurs-canadiens/">Developpez.com</a>.
Mourad Debbabi, with the Concordia Institute for Information Systems
Engineering, was also interviewed on Radio-Canada radio's </span><i><span style="font-family: &quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;">Je l'ai vu √† la radio</span></i><span style="font-family: &quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;"> and <i><a href="http://www.radio-canada.ca/audio-video/pop.shtml#urlMedia=http://www.radio-canada.ca/Medianet/2011/CBF/Desautels201103091509_1.asx">D<span lang="EN-CA">√©sautels</span></a></i></span><span style="font-family: &quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;"> </span><span style="font-family: &quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;">regarding the study.</span><br /><span style="font-family: 'Arial','sans-serif';"><br />The original story was published in the March 7 edition of the <i>Concordia Journal</i>.<br /><br />
<hr>
<br /><b>Identifying 'anonymous' email authors</b><br /><i>by Chris Atack</i><br /><br />A team of researchers from Concordia University has developed an effective new technique to determine the authorship of anonymous emails. Tests showed their method has a high level of accuracy - and unlike many other methods of ascertaining authorship, it can provide presentable evidence in courts of law. The new technique is profiled in a <a href="http://www.dfrws.org/2008/proceedings/p42-iqbal.pdf">study</a> published in <i>Digital Investigation.</i><br /><br /><img style="margin: 0px 0px 20px 20px; float: right;" class="mt-image-right" alt="Fung.jpg" src="http://newsfeed.encs.concordia.ca/encs_test/Fung.jpg" height="183" width="220" />"In the past few years, we've seen an alarming increase in the number of cybercrimes involving anonymous emails," says study co-author <a href="http://users.encs.concordia.ca/%7Efung/">Benjamin Fung</a>, a professor of <a href="http://www.ciise.concordia.ca/">Information Systems Engineering</a> at Concordia University and an expert in data mining - extracting useful, previously unknown knowledge from a large volume of raw data. "These emails can transmit threats or child pornography, facilitate communications between criminals or carry viruses."<br /><br />While police can often use the IP address to locate the house or apartment where an email originated, they may find many people at that address. They need a reliable, effective way to determine which of several suspects has written the emails under investigation.<br /><br />Fung and his colleagues developed a novel method of authorship attribution to meet this need, based on techniques used in speech recognition and data mining. Their approach relies on the identification of frequent patterns - unique combinations of features that recur in a suspect's emails.<br /><br />To determine whether a suspect has authored the target email, they first identify the patterns found in emails written by the subject. Then, they filter out any of these patterns which are also found in the emails of other suspects. The remaining frequent patterns are unique to the author of the emails being analyzed. They constitute the suspect's 'write-print,' a distinctive identifier like a fingerprint. "Let's say the anonymous email contains typos or grammatical mistakes, or is written entirely in lowercase letters," says Fung. "We use those special characteristics to create a write-print. Using this method, we can even determine with a high degree of accuracy who wrote a given email, and infer the gender, nationality and education level of the author."<br /><br />To test the accuracy of their technique, Fung and his colleagues examined the Enron Email Dataset, a collection which contains over 200,000 real-life emails from 158 employees of the Enron Corporation. Using a sample of 10 emails written by each of 10 subjects (100 emails in all), they were able to identify authorship with an accuracy of 80% to 90%.<br /><br />"Our technique was designed to provide credible evidence that can be presented in a court of law," says Fung. "For evidence to be admissible, investigators need to explain how they have reached their conclusions. Our method allows them to do this."<br /><br />The new authorship identification technique was developed in collaboration with <a href="http://users.encs.concordia.ca/%7Edebbabi/">Mourad Debbabi</a>, a Concordia expert in cyber forensics, and PhD student Farkhund Iqbal. "Our different backgrounds allowed us to apply data mining techniques to real-life problems in cyber forensics," says Fung. "This is an excellent illustration of how effective interdisciplinary research can be."<br /><br /></span>
		</div>
	
	</div>
</div>
<div class="clear">&nbsp;</div>



    

    <div id="entry-317">
	<div class="entry-header">
		<h2 class="asset-name entry-title"><a href="http://www.encs.concordia.ca/news-and-events/entry.php?a=2011/03/concordia-researcher-helps-explain-natural-wonders.php">Concordia researcher helps explain natural wonders </a></h2>
		<div class="entry-meta" title="2011-03-07T15:05:16-05:00">Monday Mar  7, 2011
                </div>
	</div>

	<div class="entry-content">
	
		<div class="entry-body">
			Research coming out of Concordia often impacts our day-to-day lives. Groundbreaking insights into everything from bullying to obesity, domestic violence to power tools, have given us a better understanding of how the world around us works. Lately, the findings of one Concordia researcher have been reaching for the sky...and beyond! <br /><br /><div align="center"><img alt="Vatistas-hurricane-saturn-web.jpg" src="http://newsfeed.encs.concordia.ca/encs_test/Vatistas-hurricane-saturn-web.jpg" class="mt-image-center" style="text-align: center; display: block; margin: 0pt auto 20px;" height="291" width="440" /><font style="font-size: 0.8em;"><i>The research of George Vatistas has been used to predict hurricanes and explain the hexagonal shape of the jet-stream that flows over Saturn's north pole<br /></i></font><br /></div>In 2008, <a href="http://www.me.concordia.ca/people/faculty/vatistas">George Vatistas</a>, Professor in the <a href="http://www.me.concordia.ca/">Department of Mechanical and Industrial Engineering</a>, within Concordia's Faculty of Engineering and Computer Science, <a href="http://cjournal.concordia.ca/archives/20080417/researchers_confirm_124yearold_theorem.php">made headlines</a> when he definitively proved that Nobel Prize winner J. J. Thomson's theory on the stability of ring satellite vortices was pragmatically sound. For decades prior to that, Vatistas had been making waves with his research into vortices. Now, that work is being taken up by scientists from south of the border to help explain natural mysteries.<br /><br />In the latest edition of the <i><a href="http://journals.ametsoc.org/toc/atsc/0/0">Journal of the Atmospheric Sciences</a></i> (the renowned peer-reviewed journal of the American Meteorological Society), meteorologist Vincent Wood (from The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration-Severe Storms Laboratory) along with Luther White (from University of Oklahoma-Department of Mathematics) cite Vatistas's research over 20 times in their article, "A New Parametric Model of Vortex Tangential-Wind Profiles: Development, Testing and Verification."<br /><br />The article looks uses what they call the "Vatistas Model" to help predict hurricanes and typhoons--natural disasters that cause substantial losses in life and property worldwide every year. Co-authors Wood and White extend Vatistas's basic vortex model with the aim to characterize realistic-looking wind profiles encountered in dust devils, waterspouts, tornadoes, meso-cyclones and tropical cyclones. Through this application of Vatistas's research, meteorologists will be able to more accurately predict the intensity of these catastrophic vortices and shed light on the scientific reasons for their destructive nature.<br /><br />Meanwhile, the research on satellite vortices has been recently used as
an example of laboratory finding in support of a natural phenomenon
beyond the earthly realities of tornadoes.
: the unique hexagonal shape of the jet-stream that flows over Saturn's north pole. First observed by NASA's Voyager mission, the pattern has persisted for over thirty years. In an article entitled "Emergence of polar jet polygons from jet instabilities in a Saturn model," in the latest edition of <i><a href="http://www.elsevier.com/wps/find/journaldescription.cws_home/622843/description#description">Icarus</a></i>, a peer-reviewed journal devoted to the publication of original contributions in the field of Solar System studies, co-authors Raul Morales-Juberias, Kunio M. Syanagi, Timothy E. Dowling, and Andrew P. Ingersoil use Vatistas's boratory findings on vortex patterns to provide an
example of an earthly experimental evidence to this seemingly unnatural
shape.
<br /><br />With work being done by Concordia researchers having such far-reaching impact, it is no wonder that the Faculty of Engineering and Computer Science is quickly emerging as a leader in the field. Vatistas has already seen his work form the basis of a generalized approach to wake characterization in fixed wing aircraft, helicopters, ship propulsion, the aerodynamics of insect-like flapping wings, gas turbine engines, wind turbines, optics, acoustics, and many others. He expects that his research will continue to have far-reaching implications in the years to come and looks forward to sharing his results with his colleagues at Concordia and around the world.<br />
		</div>
	
	</div>
</div>
<div class="clear">&nbsp;</div>



    

    <div id="entry-316">
	<div class="entry-header">
		<h2 class="asset-name entry-title"><a href="http://www.encs.concordia.ca/news-and-events/entry.php?a=2011/03/knex-tower-blasts-off-in-ev-atrium.php">K'Nex Tower Blasts off in EV Atrium!</a></h2>
		<div class="entry-meta" title="2011-03-03T17:05:28-05:00">Thursday Mar  3, 2011
                </div>
	</div>

	<div class="entry-content">
	
		<div class="entry-body">
			As part of the festivities for Engineering Week, the Concordia Chapter of Women in Engineering has built a colossal replica of the Space Shuttle &amp; launch pad... entirely out of pieces of K'Nex!<br /><object height="300" width="400"> <param name="flashvars" value="offsite=true&amp;lang=en-us&amp;page_show_url=%2Fphotos%2Fencs-concordia%2Fsets%2F72157626190090854%2Fshow%2F&amp;page_show_back_url=%2Fphotos%2Fencs-concordia%2Fsets%2F72157626190090854%2F&amp;set_id=72157626190090854&amp;jump_to=" /> <param name="movie" value="http://www.flickr.com/apps/slideshow/show.swf?v=71649" /> <param name="allowFullScreen" value="true" /><embed type="application/x-shockwave-flash" src="http://www.flickr.com/apps/slideshow/show.swf?v=71649" allowfullscreen="true" flashvars="offsite=true&lang=en-us&page_show_url=%2Fphotos%2Fencs-concordia%2Fsets%2F72157626190090854%2Fshow%2F&page_show_back_url=%2Fphotos%2Fencs-concordia%2Fsets%2F72157626190090854%2F&set_id=72157626190090854&jump_to=" height="300" width="400"></object><br /><br />The team of students worked tirelessly to complete the project, spending long hours snapping their building blocks into place. Their efforts were amply rewarded when the Discovery Channel paid them a visit, shooting a segment for the Daily Planet TV show. <br /><br />To officially mark the completion of this impressive project, Dr. Robin Drew (Dean of the Faculty of Engineering and Computer Science) was raised high above the construction site in an industrial lift. Once at the top of the huge structure, Dr. Drew inserted the final piece of the puzzle, and the shuttle was able to "lift off" at last!<br /><br />Be sure to stop by the atrium of the EV building, located at 1515 Ste. Catherine West to see the structure for yourself. It will be in place through mid-March.<br />
		</div>
	
	</div>
</div>
<div class="clear">&nbsp;</div>



